SIMPLE: omnibus
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Omnibus
<hw>Om"ni*bus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., for all, dat.
pl. from <ets>omnis</ets> all. Cf. <er>Bus</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A long vehicle, having seats for many people; a bus.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>In the 1913 Webster the term omnibus was especially applied to,
a vehicle with seats running lengthwise, used in conveying passengers
short distances.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Glass Making)</fld> <def>A sheet-iron cover for
articles in a leer or annealing arch, to protect them from
drafts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Printing)</fld> <def>A volume containing collected
and reprinted works of a single author or on a single theme.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>omnibus</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: omnibus
<hw>om"ni*bus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to or
dealing with a variety of topics at one time; <as>as, <ex>omnibus</ex>
legislation; an <ex>omnibus</ex> budget bill</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Omnibus bill</b></col>, a legislative bill which provides
for a number of miscellaneous enactments or appropriations.
<mark>[Parliamentary Cant, U.S.]</mark> -- <col><b>Omnibus
box</b></col>, <cd>a large box in a theater, on a level with the stage
and having communication with it.</cd> <mark>[Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Thackeray.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Omnicorporeal</ent>⟦br⟧
